Section 8 Curtailment
A. To the extent that Transporter's facilities are unable on any Gas Day, by reason of Force Majeure or otherwise, to provide delivery to meet Shipper's Daily Transportation Quantity, Transporter's interruptible customers shall first be curtailed. After all of Transporter's interruptible customers have been curtailed, Shipper's Daily Transportation Quantity shall, if necessary, be curtailed on a pro rata basis with Transporter's other firm obligations at the affected Receipt Point(s).

Section 7 Force Majeure
A. The term "Force Majeure" shall mean any unforeseeable cause beyond the reasonable control of the party claiming Force Majeure, which by exercise of due foresight such party could not reasonably have been expected to avoid and which, by the exercise of due diligence, it is unable to overcome, including, but not limited to: acts of God; acts of a public enemy; expropriation or confiscation of facilities; acts of declared or undeclared war; acts of terrorism; public disorder; rebellion or sabotage; revolution; epidemic; landslide; lightning; fire; hurricane; earthquake; flood; riot; explosion; partial or entire failure of utilities; breakage or accident to gas transportation or distribution facilities or equipment or lines of pipe; freezing of wells or pipelines; strikes; work stoppage associated with labor dispute; injunction or quarantine; changes in Applicable Laws subsequent to the Effective Date hereof; or action or inaction by any Governmental Authority.
B. Except for Shipper's obligation to make payments as may be included under a Transportation Service Agreement, the parties shall be excused from performing their respective obligations under such Transportation Service Agreement and shall be liable in damages or otherwise if and to the extent that they are unable to so perform or are prevented from performing by Force Majeure, provided that:
(1) the non-performing party, as promptly as practicable after the occurrence of the Force Majeure, gives the other party written notice describing the particulars of the occurrence; in the event the Force Majeure outage would cause Transporter to be unable to transport supply for the current or next Gas Day, Transporter will notify Shipper by phone as soon as practicable;
(2) the suspension of performance is of no greater scope and of no greater duration than is reasonably required by the Force Majeure;
(3) the non-performing party uses all reasonable efforts to remedy its inability to perform; and
(4) as soon as the non-performing party is able to resume performance of its obligations hereunder, it give prompt written notice thereof to the other party.

Section 6 Measurement and Metering
A. Measurement at Delivery Point(s). Transporter shall install meters at Delivery Point(s) as necessary to accurately and reliably measure volumes of Gas delivered to Shipper in accordance with generally accepted industry practices. If the use of electronic or other types of flow computers is utilized, they shall be installed, and volumes shall be calculated, in accordance with generally accepted industry practices. Shipper may install, maintain, and operate at its own expense, such check measuring equipment as it desires, provided that such equipment shall be so installed so as not to interfere with the operation of Transporter's facilities, including measuring equipment.
B. Metering. Transporter shall make available to Shipper isolated secure connection points from Transporter's metering equipment for Shipper, at Shipper's sole expense, to receive electronic signals providing pressure, flow rates, and total usage. Transporter shall also provide Shipper, on a commercially reasonable basis, a daily usage report showing actual deliveries of Gas to the Delivery Point. Such daily usage reports shall reflect a one-day calendar lag in information due to the download of metering information to report. If there are any differences between the daily usage report made available each day and the daily metered usage downloaded at the completion of the monthly billing period, Shipper and Transporter will accept the latter information as the usage information that will govern as to monthly billing information.

Section 10 New Facilities
A. Transporter shall not be required to provide any requested transportation service that would require construction or acquisition by Transporter of any new facilities or expansion of Transporter's existing facilities. Transporter, in its sole discretion, and subject to regulatory approvals, may agree to construct or acquire new facilities, or expand existing facilities, to provide service requested by any Shipper. In such event, Shipper agrees to reimburse Transporter for the total incremental cost of the new facilities or expansion of existing facilities, unless otherwise mutually agreed in writing. Transporter shall determine method of reimbursement, either lump sum, installment, or as-used.
B. To the extent Transporter agrees to construct or acquire any new facilities or expand existing facilities, any such facilities shall be contracted, maintained, owned and operated by Transporter, except as may be mutually agreed in writing. The design and installation of all facilities shall be in accordance with the specifications determined by Transporter in its sole, reasonable discretion.

Section 9 Creditworthiness
A. Transporter shall not be required to perform or continue to perform service on behalf of any Shipper (i) that has applied for bankruptcy under any chapter of the Bankruptcy Code, (ii) that fails to make prompt and full payment to Transporter when due for transportation and balancing services rendered by Transporter, or (iii) for which Transporter has reasonable grounds for insecurity as to Shipper's performance of its obligations under any transaction governed hereby. If any event set forth in (i), (ii) or (iii) shall occur, in addition to any other rights or remedies available to Transporter, it may in writing demand adequate assurance of due performance and until it receives such assurance, may suspend any performance for which it has not already been paid.
B. Adequate assurance of performance of the type described in A. above shall include (i) posting of a letter of credit in form and from a financial institution acceptable to Transporter; (ii) cash prepayment; or (iii) delivery of other forms of security acceptable to the Transporter. Shipper's failure to deliver adequate assurance properly demanded within two business days of receiving Transporter's demand therefore shall constitute a breach of the applicable transportation transaction, entitling Transporter to (i) terminate any or all transportation transactions with Shipper, (ii) liquidate gas balances in Transporter's possession and applying the resulting funds to the payment of all amounts owed and that become owed for services under any transportation transactions governed by this Statement of Operating Conditions, and (iii) seek all other remedies available for breach for all applicable transportation transactions.

Section 1 Definitions
1.A Applicable Laws shall mean all applicable federal, state and local laws, ordinances, rules, regulations, orders, decrees or other duly authorized actions of any Governmental Authority having jurisdiction over the parties, the Transporter's distribution facilities and/or the transactions under any service agreement for firm interstate transportation service.
1.B Btu shall mean British Thermal Unit and, where appropriate, the plural thereof.
1.C Daily Transportation Quantity shall mean the quantity of gas that Shipper nominates for delivery from the Receipt Point(s) to the Delivery Point on a particular Gas Day.
1.D Dekatherm or Dth shall mean a quantity of heat equal to ten therms or one million British Thermal Units (one MMBtu).
1.E Delivery Point shall mean the point of interconnection between the facilities of the Transporter and Shipper as may be more fully described in the Transportation Service Agreement.
1.F FERC or Commission shall mean Federal Energy Regulatory Commission or its successor agency.
1.G Gas or Natural Gas shall mean any mixture of hydrocarbons or of hydrocarbons and non-combustible gases, in a gaseous state, that meets the quality standards contained in these general terms.
1.H Governmental Authority shall mean any federal, state, local or municipal governmental body, any governmental, regulatory or administrative agency, commission, body or other authority exercising or entitled to exercise any administrative, executive, judicial, legislative, policy, regulatory or taxing authority or power; or any court or governmental tribunal.
1.I Interstate Pipeline shall mean any interstate pipeline that is directly interconnected with Transporter such that it is able to deliver gas to the Receipt Point.
1.J Maximum Daily Quantity or MDQ shall mean the maximum quantity of gas net of fuel loss which Transporter shall be obligated to transport and deliver in the aggregate from the Receipt Point(s) and deliver through Transporter's distribution facilities to the Delivery Point.
1.K MMBtu shall mean one million British Thermal Units.
1.L Receipt Point(s) shall mean the point(s) of interconnection between the facilities of Transporter and Interstate Pipeline as more fully described in the Transportation Service Agreement.
1.M Shipper shall mean any entity entering into a Transportation Service Agreement with Transporter to receive service in accordance with the terms and conditions set forth herein, or its successors or assigns.
1.O Transportation Service Agreement shall mean any contract of Transporter providing transportation service to a Shipper.
1.P Transporter shall mean Wisconsin Power and Light Company, its successors or assigns.
1.Q WPL Retail Gas Tariff shall mean all tariffs on file with the Public Service Commission of Wisconsin which have been filed by Wisconsin Power and Light Company and accepted by the PSCW and which govern the provision of natural gas delivery and balancing service to retail customers of Wisconsin Power and Light Company.

Section 2 Applicability
A. Transporter shall provide firm interstate transportation service by receiving Daily Transportation Quantities delivered by Shipper to the Receipt Point(s) and by redelivering such quantities, pursuant to the terms and conditions herein and as specified in the Transportation Service Agreement, to the Delivery Point.

Section 5 Billing and Payment
A. Billing. Transporter shall render invoices for service rendered to Shipper by the fifteenth day of each month. Such invoices shall include a statement showing the amount due applicable to the preceding month, along with a computation of the amount due and payable. When information necessary for billing purposes is in the control of Shipper, Shipper shall furnish such information to Transporter on or before the third day of the month. Both Transporter and Shipper have the right to examine at reasonable times upon prior notice and at its own expense, books, records and charts of the other to the extent necessary to verify the accuracy of any statement, charge or computation made under or pursuant to any of the provisions hereof.
B. Payment. Shipper shall pay all invoices rendered for service within ten days of receiving the statement from the Transporter. Payments by Shipper to Transporter shall be made in the form of wire transfer in immediately available funds directed to a bank account designated by Transporter's Controller, unless otherwise agreed. If payment differs from the invoiced amount, remittance detail should be provided with the payment within two Business Days of the payment due date. Interest on the unpaid portion of the bill shall accrue at the current rate as set forth in Section 154.501(d) of the Commission's rules and regulations, from the due date until the date of payment. If such failure to pay continues for thirty days after payment is due, Transporter, in addition to any other remedy it may have hereunder, may suspend further delivery of Gas until such amount is paid.
C. Billing Disputes. If Shipper in good faith disputes the amount of any such bill or part thereof and pays to Transporter such amounts, if any, it concedes to be correct and, at any time thereafter within thirty days of a demand made by Transporter, furnishes a good and sufficient surety bond in an amount and with surety satisfactory to Transporter or other assurance acceptable to Transporter, guaranteeing payment to Transporter of the unpaid amount, then Transporter shall not be entitled to suspend further delivery of such Gas unless and until default be made in the conditions of such bond.
D. Error Adjustments. In the event an error is discovered in the amount billed in any statement rendered by Transporter, such error shall be adjusted within thirty days of the determination thereof, provided that claim therefore shall have been made within 30 days of discovery of such error, but in any event within six months from the date of such statement, provided, however, that the party harmed by the adjustment shall have up to three months to dispute such adjustment. The riming of billing claims and adjustments referenced in the previous shall not apply in the case of deliberate omission or misrepresentation or mutual mistake of fact. Parties' other statutory or contractual rights shall not be diminished by this standard. If parties are unable to agree on the adjustment of any claimed error, any resort by either of the parties to legal proceedings shall be commenced within 15 months after the supposed cause of action is alleged to have arisen, or shall thereafter be forever barred.
E. Final invoices and payments. All invoices and payments, other than those related to Taxes, shall be final unless questioned within twelve months from the date of such invoice or payment. Any error discovered as a result of a timely claim shall be adjusted within thirty days of the determination of such errors.
F. Taxes. Shipper shall reimburse Transporter for all taxes that may be levied upon and/or paid by Transporter with respect to the service performed under this Operating Statement. Shipper shall be responsible for establishing any exemption from taxes and shall provide satisfactory evidence of such exemption to Transporter.

Section 4 Gas Deliveries
A. The Maximum Daily Quantity (MDQ) of Gas that Transporter shall be obligated to transport and deliver on behalf of Shipper, on a firm basis, shall be as set forth in the Transportation Service Agreement, measured at the delivery point(s). The MDQ shall not exceed the Shipper's entitlement on the Interstate Pipeline at the Receipt Point(s).
B. Daily Transportation Quantity Nominations. Shipper shall conform to the nomination and confirmation deadlines of Interstate Pipeline. Transporter shall not be required to accept Intra-day 2 nomination changes requested by Shipper. Upon receiving nominations, and conditioned upon acceptance and confirmation of such nominations by Interstate Pipeline, Transporter shall receive such quantities at the Receipt Point(s) and redeliver such quantities to Shipper at the Delivery Point. Daily Transportation Quantity nominations shall be considered first through the meter at the Receipt Point(s).
C. Upstream Interstate Pipeline Transportation. It shall be Shipper's responsibility to arrange with the Interstate Pipeline for the delivery of Shipper's Gas to the Receipt Point(s). Shipper shall be responsible for any Interstate Pipeline imbalance charges, penalties, or other applicable charges incurred by, or applicable to, Shipper.
D. Gas Quality Specifications. Shipper shall meet the quality specifications required by the Interstate Pipeline.

Section 3 Statement of Rates and Charges
A. The maximum transportation charge for transportation service shall be the maximum rate approved by the FERC for transportation under the blanket certificate issued by the FERC. Notwithstanding the foregoing sentence, the rate to be charged for transportation may be agreed to between Transporter and Shipper, provided that such agreed to rate may not exceed the maximum unit rate approved by the FERC for such transportation, and provided further that such agreed to rate may not be less than any minimum rate, if any, as defined by the FERC.
B. Transporter's maximum rate for transportation service shall be determined pursuant to Section 284.123(b)(1)(ii) of FERC's regulations. Transporter reserves the right to file for a higher maximum rate at any time and the maximum rate which Shipper agrees to pay shall be revised to equal such higher maximum.
C. The maximum rate approved by FERC and in effect at the time the instant statement is filed is shown in Exhibit A..
D. Balancing. Shipper and Transporter shall make arrangements for the balancing of receipts and deliveries, including any arrangements to accommodate imbalances between Shipper and Interstate Pipeline. Shippers shall endeavor to fully utilize in each monthly billing period all transportation quantities nominated and received by the Transporter on their behalf. At the end of each billing period, any differences between the transportation quantities received and delivered must be brought into balance and are subject to the prior month purchase reference prices. If Shipper gas deliveries are greater than Shipper gas received, the difference between deliveries and receipts shall be subject to overtake rates. If Shipper gas received is greater than Shipper gas delivered, the difference between receipts and deliveries shall be subject to undertake rates.
E. Lost and Unaccounted-For Gas. The quantity of transportation gas received from the transporting pipeline will be charged, upon delivery to Shipper, by a fixed amount, which shall represent compensation for Lost and Unaccounted-For gas. This charge may be adjusted by the Transporter from time to time; however, a fixed loss percentage is used with adjustments made. See Exhibit A for the fixed loss percentage approved by FERC and in effect at the time the instant statement is filed.
